To find the time \emph{t\textsubscript{empty}} when the height
\emph{h(t\textsubscript{empty})} is zero we calculate

\begin{align*}0 = h(t_{\text{empty}}) = \left(h_0^{2/3}- \frac23 kt_{\text{empty}}\right)^{3/2}.\end{align*}

Solving for \emph{t\textsubscript{empty}} yields

\begin{align*}t_{\text{empty}} = \frac{3}{2k} h_0^{2/3}.\end{align*}

\emph{Note: The differential equation is no longer valid after this
time, because a negative height of fluid in a tank does not make sense.}
